<TITLE> Saifur, Mojaheed, 7 others face arrest </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 6 (bdnews24.com) - A Dhaka Court has issued arrest warrants against nine accused in Barapukuria coal mine corruption case, including former ministers of the immediate past BNP-led government Saifur Rahman and Ali Ahsan Mohammad Mojaheed. Dhaka metropolitan senior special judge Md Azizul Haque issued the warrants and ordered submission of reports of arrest to the court by Oct 12. The other seven facing arrest are former minister Aminul Haq, former state minister for energy AKM Mosharraf Hossain, former energy secretary Nazrul Islam, former chairman of Petrobangla SR Osmany, former director (mines and minerals) Moyeenul Ahsan, former managing director of Barapukuria Coal Mining Company Ltd Sirajul Islam, and chairman of Hosaf Group Moazzem Hossain, the local agent of the Chinese firm which was awarded the running of the coal mine. No warrant of arrest has been issued against the five accused that secured bail in the case from High Court. They are former prime minister Khaleda Zia, former ministers Motiur Rahman Nizami, MK Anwar, M Shamsul Islam and Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan. BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia secured four months bail from the High Court on Sept 8. Md Abdur Razzak, lawyer of Jamaat-e-Islami chief Nizami, told bdnews24.com: "The High Court granted Motiur Rahman Nizami bail in the case on August 26 until submission of the charge sheet. He will appear before the court on Oct 12 and make a fresh appeal for bail." As two other charge sheeted in the case, former ministers Khandker Mosharraf Hossain and Altaf Hossain Chowdhury, are in jail in connection with separate cases, the court ordered jail authorities to produce them before the court on the same date. ACC's investigation officer in the case Abul Kashem Faquir submitted charge sheets against 16 people, including Khaleda Zia, to Dhaka Chief Metropolitan Magistrate's Court Sunday evening. The case was filed with Shahbag thana on February 26 this year on charges of irregularities and corruption in awarding the production, management and maintenance work of Barapukuria coalmine to a Chinese firm. The charge sheets said the agreement with Chinese firm Consortium of China National Machinery Import and Export Corporation (CMC) caused losses of Tk 158.71 crore to the government. bdnew
